<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>08. "The Principle and the Proof." Kohler Automatic Power and Light; Kohler, WI; 1924.</strong><br />       <p>Many of the 27 million visitors arriving to the 1893 World&rsquo;s Columbian Exposition had likely never seen electricity in action before. Fifteen years later, only 8% of the housing units in the nation had electricity in the home and by 1920, a mere 35%. Cheaper and more efficient than the steam engine, electricity had a transformative potential that remained unrealized in the lives of most Americans.</p>

<p>As the country returned to a peacetime economy, utility firms were left with excess capacity and manufacturing companies with idle plants and equipment that demanded the development of new markets.<sup><a href="3512#fn9" id="ref9">9</a></sup> In addition, government reformers began appealing for more stringent regulation and the government&rsquo;s entry into the electricity business.<sup><a href="3512#fn10" id="ref10">10</a></sup>Given these forces, the electrical industry had no choice but to &ldquo;raise the nation&rsquo;s electrical consciousness&rdquo; using both the media and corporate advocacy campaigns—which produced promotional literature such as this—to &ldquo;promote electrification, suggest new uses of electricity, discredit public power proponents, and stave off the regulators.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3512#fn11" id="ref11">11</a></sup></p>

<p>Motivation aside, their campaign was largely a success: by 1930, 68% of Americans had access to electricity in the home.</p>
<br />
<sup id="fn9">9. Andrew Feldman, &ldquo;Selling the &lsquo;Electrical Idea&rsquo;: The Campaign to Electrify America in the 1920s.&rdquo; <em>Argumentation</em>, vol.8, no.4 (1994): 377. <a href="3512#ref9" title="Jump back to footnote 9 in the text.">↩</a></sup>
    <p><sup id="fn10">10. Ibid.<a href="3512#ref10" title="Jump back to footnote 10 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p>
    <p><sup id="fn11">11. Ibid.<a href="3512#ref11" title="Jump back to footnote 11 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p><br /><br />
    	 "Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs," Case 3, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br />
<br />
<a href="https://digital-libraries.artic.edu/cdm/ref/collection/mqc/id/68833">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
    </div><!--/artwork-details-->
